# 5 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring: Prices, Settings & On Hand {{year}}

A 5 carat pear shaped diamond ring at Blue Nile presents a market reality unlike any other carat tier: natural GIA Ideal-cut pear diamonds at 5ct are effectively absent from Blue Nile's live inventory — not temporarily, but structurally. Lab grown 5ct pear stones start at [$7,505 for an IGI 4.59ct E-VVS1 Excellent](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27310622?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and reach [$38,935 for a GIA 4.61ct D-FL Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29357210?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — with a complete ring total running $8,305–$43,000+ depending on stone grade and setting metal. This guide covers everything about the 5ct pear shaped diamond ring: why natural inventory doesn't exist at this tier, every available lab grown stone with prices, ring settings, how a 5ct pear looks on the hand, and the exact builds that produce the best 5ct pear ring at every budget.

The 5ct pear shaped diamond ring sits in a category where normal diamond shopping logic breaks entirely. At 1ct, Blue Nile carries 30+ natural GIA pear options; at 4ct, four stones; at 5ct, the answer is typically zero. A 5ct natural GIA pear diamond of Ideal quality doesn't exist in Blue Nile's catalog because those stones, when they exist at all, move through private sale, auction, or estate channels at prices that start above $150,000 for a single stone. At approximately 17×11mm face-up — roughly a small paperclip in dimension — a 5ct pear shaped diamond covers the full width of most fingers from edge to edge.

## TL;DR: 5 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring — What to Know

- **Natural GIA 5ct pear:** Zero Ideal-cut stones available on Blue Nile at this tier. This is not a restocking delay — see The Empty Tier below. Natural 5ct pear acquisition happens via auction and private dealers at $150,000–$500,000+.
- **Lab grown 5ct pear ring:** Stone [$7,505 IGI 4.59ct E-VVS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27310622?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + solitaire $800 = ring total ~$8,305. Best value 5ct build at Blue Nile.
- **Top lab stone at 5ct:** [$25,432 IGI 4.97ct D-FL Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — the closest to a true 5.00ct pear in Blue Nile's catalog. Add a platinum halo ($4,005) = ring total ~$29,437.
- **GIA lab 5ct pear:** [$8,637 GIA 4.54ct D-VVS1 Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27420800?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — GIA-certified lab stone at 4.5ct with D colorless grade. Ring total with solitaire ~$9,437.
- **5ct pear on hand:** At ~17×11mm, a 5ct pear covers the full width of most fingers. This is the tier where the diamond becomes the dominant architectural element — the ring setting exists to hold the stone, not to frame it.
- **Ring settings for 5ct:** Solitaire (14K WG ~$800, platinum ~$1,500); [sidestone 14K YG $1,820](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-sidestone-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-4-ct-tw-item-192877?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational); halo [14K WG $3,570](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-by-james-allen-item-310842?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) or [platinum $4,005](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-310847?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). V-tip prong is non-negotiable at 5ct.
- **Contrarian Truth:** The [$25,432 IGI 4.97ct D-FL](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) lab grown stone is, face-up, indistinguishable from a natural 5ct D-FL pear that would cost $200,000+. The origin is in the certificate, not in the diamond. At the 5ct tier, this is not a compromise — it is the only rational path for ring buyers who want 5ct pear face-up size.
- **Priority:** → The [IGI 4.97ct D-FL Ideal at $25,432](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in a 14K white gold solitaire ($800) delivers a true near-5ct pear ring at $26,232 total. Budget buyers: the [IGI 4.59ct E-VVS1 at $7,505](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27310622?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + solitaire at ~$8,305 total is the correct entry-point 5ct-tier pear ring build.

## 5 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Price: Natural GIA

Natural GIA-certified pear diamonds at 5ct are the rarest inventory tier in Blue Nile's entire catalog — rarer than 4ct natural pear, rarer than any other shape at comparable weight. At the 4ct natural pear tier, Blue Nile carries four stones; at 5ct, the count is effectively zero. This is not a fulfillment gap or a seasonal inventory variation: it reflects geological supply reality at the 5ct+ weight class for fancy-cut diamonds.

A natural pear diamond rough crystal large enough to yield a 5ct polished stone with GIA Ideal proportions is extraordinarily rare. Most 5ct+ natural pear crystals in circulation carry inclusions that preclude VS or higher clarity grades, have color grades below H, or exhibit severe bow-tie effects that disqualify them from Ideal or Excellent cut designations. The stones that do pass GIA Ideal grading at 5ct natural pear move through Sotheby's, Christie's, and private dealer networks — not through retail platforms like Blue Nile.

**What natural 5ct pear costs when it exists:** Auction records for natural GIA-certified pear diamonds at 5ct+ show price ranges of $150,000–$500,000+ for the stone alone, depending on color, clarity, and provenance. A natural 5ct D-FL GIA pear has sold above $400,000 at international auction. A natural 5ct G-VS1 GIA pear, when available, would realistically price at $120,000–$180,000 based on per-carat natural pear price progression from the 4ct tier. For the complete pear diamond pricing hierarchy from 1ct to 4ct natural, see the [Loose Pear Diamonds guide](/loose-pear-diamonds).

For buyers whose acquisition pathway is Blue Nile, the 5ct natural GIA pear market does not exist in retail form. The correct shopping strategy at this tier is lab grown — not as a fallback, but as the functional product.

## The Empty Tier

The Empty Tier is the specific market condition at 5ct natural GIA pear: an entire carat weight class with no accessible retail inventory. Unlike smaller carat tiers where low stock means two or three stones instead of thirty, the 5ct natural pear tier at Blue Nile shows zero qualifying stones on a typical day — not low stock, not limited selection, but an empty shelf.

This condition is structurally stable, not cyclical. The natural pear diamond supply chain has a hard yield constraint at the 5ct level: the rough crystals required simply do not produce Ideal-quality polished pear diamonds at that weight with sufficient frequency to populate a retail catalog. Blue Nile's natural pear inventory at 4ct comprises four stones — at 5ct, those four become zero, because the 5ct yield requirement eliminates the stones that would otherwise appear at 4ct+ weights with suboptimal proportions or color.

Understanding The Empty Tier matters because it changes the shopping decision entirely. At 1ct or 2ct, a buyer choosing lab grown is making a value optimization within a market that includes both natural and lab options. At the 5ct tier, a buyer choosing lab grown is simply choosing the only product that exists — the decision is not between natural and lab, but between buying a 5ct pear ring or not buying one. The Empty Tier makes lab grown the default, not an alternative.

