**Reading the 5ct lab grown table:** The $7,505 IGI E-VVS1 at 4.59ct is the correct entry-point stone — E color is one grade below D but visually identical in any setting, and VVS1 clarity at 4.59ct is exceptional. The [$8,637 GIA D-VVS1 Ideal at 4.54ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27420800?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) offers GIA certification for buyers who specifically want GIA-only documentation at a near-D colorless level with a $1,132 premium over the IGI entry. The [$25,432 IGI 4.97ct D-FL](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the closest to a true 5.00ct pear on Blue Nile — 0.03ct from the target weight, D colorless, Flawless, Ideal cut. The [$38,935 GIA 4.61ct D-FL](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29357210?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the premium GIA-certified lab option — smaller than the 4.97ct IGI but carrying GIA's D-FL designation at an $13,503 premium over the IGI.

**Price jump from $20,792 to $23,027:** The three stones priced $20,792–$23,232 differ mainly by certification (GCAL vs IGI) and clarity (FL vs IF) rather than carat weight. GCAL is a well-respected lab for lab grown diamonds; IF is effectively indistinguishable from FL at the eye level. The $20,792 GCAL D-FL at 4.52ct represents genuine value within this tier — buyers who understand lab certification can save ~$2,200 by choosing GCAL over IGI at equivalent grade.

**Certification comparison at 5ct lab grown:** GIA has expanded its lab grown grading significantly, and its pear grades are treated with the same rigor as natural stone grading. IGI is the highest-volume lab grown certifier and its grades are consistent and accepted industry-wide. GCAL (Gem Certification & Assurance Lab) offers full optical brilliance reporting alongside standard grading and is a strong choice specifically for lab grown buyers who want cut performance data. For the complete lab grown vs natural pear diamond analysis, see the [Pear Cut Diamond guide](/pear-cut-diamond).

## The Lab Sovereign

The Lab Sovereign describes the position lab grown pear diamonds occupy uniquely at the 5ct tier: not as a value alternative to natural, but as the sovereign product — the only accessible option that exists. At smaller carat weights, lab grown is a choice within a market. At 5ct pear, lab grown is the market.

This matters for how buyers frame their decision. A buyer purchasing the [$25,432 IGI 4.97ct D-FL](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is not compromising on origin — they are purchasing the only form of a 5ct D-FL Ideal pear diamond that is accessible to any retail buyer at any price below six figures. The natural equivalent, when it exists, moves through channels that require auction registration, private dealer relationships, and transaction processes that take months. The Lab Sovereign at 5ct is not cheaper natural — it is a different product that happens to be measurably identical in optical performance.

The practical implication for ring design: buyers can allocate budget toward the setting, the band, and long-term wear quality rather than absorbing a six-figure stone cost. A [$25,432 IGI D-FL 4.97ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in a platinum halo at [$4,005](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/pear-shape-side-stone-diamond-halo-engagement-ring-in-platinum-by-james-allen-item-310847?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) produces a total ring of ~$29,437 — a piece that, face-up on the hand, is optically equivalent to what would cost $200,000+ in natural form.

