## Color and Clarity Guide for 5ct Pear Diamond

At the 5ct face-up area (~17×11mm), color and clarity visibility rules change relative to smaller carat weights. The expanded face-up zone means color visible in a 1ct stone belly is even more visible at 5ct — and inclusions that hide easily in a 1ct table can be visible to the naked eye at 5ct face-up dimensions.

**Color at 5ct pear lab grown:** D–F is the recommended range for lab grown pear diamonds at 5ct in white gold or platinum settings. The lab grown price premium for D over E is modest relative to natural diamonds — the [$7,505 IGI E-VVS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27310622?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) vs [$8,637 GIA D-VVS1](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27420800?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) shows a $1,132 gap for a D vs E color difference — affordable for the color upgrade. G color in a 5ct pear is visible as warmth in the belly area under cool lighting; D–F is the correct floor. Yellow gold settings mask G–H color effectively and allow a slightly lower color grade without visual consequence.

**Clarity at 5ct pear lab grown:** VS1 is the practical clarity floor at 5ct pear. An SI1 inclusion that is eye-clean in a 1ct stone may be visible at 5ct face-up dimensions, particularly near the center table or along the bow-tie zone. All stones in the Blue Nile 5ct lab grown pear table are VVS1 or above — FL, IF, VVS1 — reflecting the fact that lab grown stones at this price point are typically produced at the highest grade tiers. There is no eye-visible difference between FL, IF, and VVS1 at any size; the grade distinction affects certification language, not face-up appearance.

**Fluorescence at 5ct:** Strong blue fluorescence in a D or E color pear diamond can cause a milky haziness under UV-heavy lighting environments. Lab grown stones at this tier rarely exhibit strong fluorescence; verify the fluorescence grade on the specific stone certificate before purchase. Faint or None fluorescence is the correct spec at any color grade for 5ct pear.

## Bow-Tie Effect at 5ct Pear

Every pear diamond has a bow-tie — a dark bowtie-shaped shadow that appears in the center of the stone as a result of the fancy-cut geometry blocking reflected light through the viewer's line of sight. At 5ct with a 17×11mm face-up area, the bow-tie zone is proportionally larger and more visually prominent than at 1ct or 2ct. Understanding bow-tie grading at 5ct is essential before purchase.

A bow-tie that occupies less than 20% of the stone's face-up area and has low contrast against the surrounding brilliance is acceptable at 5ct — it reads as a subtle dark zone that doesn't dominate the visual. A bow-tie that extends across 30%+ of the face-up area and presents high-contrast dark against the stone's surrounding fire is significant at 5ct and should be avoided. The key assessment tool is the stone's video: Blue Nile provides 360° video for all lab grown stones, and the bow-tie is clearly visible in video under standard studio lighting.

For the complete bow-tie grading guide, depth percentage targets, and L/W ratio recommendations that minimize bow-tie severity, see the [Pear Diamond Ideal Proportions guide](/pear-diamond-ideal-proportions). At 5ct specifically, target a depth percentage of 58–64% and a table percentage of 55–63% — the same proportion targets as at smaller sizes, but more critical to verify via video at 5ct given the expanded bow-tie zone. The pear engagement ring guide covers [how to evaluate a 5ct pear ring on hand](/pear-diamond-engagement-ring) with these proportions.

## Expert Summary

> **Farzana A., GIA Graduate Gemologist and Diamond Critic:** "The 5ct pear shaped diamond ring is the one tier where I tell every buyer the same thing regardless of budget: go lab grown, and don't apologize for it. This isn't about affordability — it's about access. Natural 5ct GIA Ideal pear diamonds don't exist in retail. Auction houses carry them once or twice a year at prices that start at $150,000 and require months of acquisition process. For anyone building a 5ct pear ring as wearable fine jewelry, lab grown is the product."

> "My grading recommendations at 5ct are different from smaller sizes. At 5ct face-up, I always push buyers toward Ideal-cut certification specifically — not Excellent, Ideal. The cut precision at 5ct determines whether the bow-tie reads as a subtle dark zone or an aggressive shadow across 30% of the stone. The [$25,432 IGI 4.97ct D-FL Ideal](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the stone I'd build around for a prestige 5ct pear ring. Request the video before clicking add to cart — every time."

> "The platinum solitaire at 5ct is not an indulgence — it's a maintenance decision. Prongs on a 5ct pear are under more mechanical stress than at smaller sizes purely from the stone's weight and the leverage a 17mm surface area creates during daily wear. Platinum prongs last longer, require less frequent re-tipping, and provide materially better tip protection for the V-prong at 5ct. If the stone budget is the [$25,432 IGI D-FL](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28917716?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), adding $1,500 for a platinum solitaire over the 14K WG option is the correct long-term decision."

