## 5 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Ring — FAQ

**Why are there no natural 5ct pear diamonds on Blue Nile?**
Natural GIA Ideal-cut pear diamonds at 5ct exist in such small quantities globally that they don't appear in retail catalogs. They move through auction houses and private dealer channels at prices starting above $150,000. Blue Nile's natural pear inventory ends effectively at 4ct — see The Empty Tier above.

**How much does a 5 carat pear shaped diamond ring cost?**
At Blue Nile, a 5ct pear diamond ring using lab grown stones starts at approximately $8,305 (IGI 4.59ct E-VVS1 + 14K WG solitaire). The near-5ct prestige build (IGI 4.97ct D-FL + platinum halo) runs ~$29,437. Natural 5ct pear rings, when accessible at all, cost $150,000–$500,000+ for the stone alone.

**What is the face-up size of a 5ct pear diamond?**
A 5ct pear diamond at ideal L/W ratio (1.55–1.65) measures approximately 17×11mm face-up. This covers the full width of most adult fingers from edge to edge.

**Is lab grown the only option for a 5ct pear ring?**
For practical purposes, yes. Natural GIA 5ct pear diamonds at Ideal cut are not available through Blue Nile and rarely appear in any retail channel. Lab grown 4.5ct–5ct IGI and GIA certified stones are the accessible product at this tier.

**Which lab certification is best for a 5ct pear diamond — GIA, IGI, or GCAL?**
All three are credible at the 5ct lab grown level. GIA carries the highest brand recognition. IGI is the most common and offers the widest stone selection. GCAL provides optical brilliance grading alongside standard grades and is a strong choice for cut-performance-focused buyers. The [$20,792 GCAL D-FL at 4.52ct](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28672077?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) represents good value for GCAL-certified 5ct pear buyers.

**Do I need a V-tip prong at 5ct?**
Yes, absolutely. The pear's pointed tip is the highest chip-risk zone on the stone. At 5ct, the tip is larger and more exposed than at smaller sizes. A V-tip prong is non-negotiable — never accept a round prong at the tip of a 5ct pear.

**What color grade should I choose for a 5ct lab grown pear?**
D–F in white gold or platinum settings. E color is the budget-correct choice — it is optically identical to D in any setting. G color is acceptable in yellow gold. At 5ct, color is more visible in the belly area than at smaller sizes; D–F is the safe floor for white metal settings.

**What clarity should I choose for a 5ct lab grown pear?**
VS1 minimum; VVS1 or above preferred. All stones in Blue Nile's current 5ct lab pear catalog are VVS1 or higher. The face-up area at 5ct (~17×11mm) means inclusions near the center table can become visible at closer inspection — FL through VVS1 eliminates this risk entirely.

**What ring size works for a 5ct pear diamond?**
A 5ct pear at 17×11mm works best on size 5–8 fingers. On very small fingers (size 4 and under), the 17mm length may extend past the natural ring zone, which affects comfort during daily wear. Buyers with smaller fingers should review stone video and confirm the L/W ratio before purchase — a shorter, wider pear (L/W 1.45–1.50) fits better on smaller fingers at this carat weight.

**How does the 5ct pear compare to the 4ct pear?**
The [4ct pear at ~15×9.5mm](/4-carat-pear-shaped-diamond) covers 80–88% of the finger width; the 5ct at ~17×11mm covers the full width edge-to-edge. The 5ct is a category shift, not a marginal size increase. Natural inventory also disappears at 5ct whereas 4ct natural GIA pear exists in a four-stone pool.

**Can I compare pear vs marquise at the 5ct tier?**
Both shapes are elongated brilliants with similar face-up size per carat; at 5ct natural, both have the same inventory problem — near-zero retail availability. For the complete comparison of both elongated shapes including face-up size, bowtie behavior, V-prong requirements, and price parity, see the [Marquise vs Pear Diamond guide](/pear-vs-marquise-diamond).

**What celebrity wears a 5ct pear diamond ring?**
Ariana Grande's engagement ring from Dalton Gomez was a large pear diamond — widely reported in the 5ct+ range. Victoria Beckham's engagement ring from David Beckham included a large pear diamond. The pear shape at 5ct is the preferred celebrity and editorial choice for maximum finger-elongating presence in formal and red-carpet contexts.

**Is a 5ct pear diamond ring appropriate for daily wear?**
With the correct V-tip prong setting and a low-to-medium profile, yes. The practical adaptation period is 2–4 weeks. High-profile cathedral settings increase snagging risk; platinum prongs reduce long-term maintenance requirements. Annual prong inspection by a jeweler is recommended at the 5ct tier to verify tip prong integrity.

**What is the resale value of a 5ct lab grown pear diamond ring?**
Lab grown diamonds have limited resale value relative to purchase price — typically 20–40% of original purchase price in secondary markets. This is consistent across all lab grown diamond sizes and shapes and reflects the declining manufacturing cost of lab grown production. Buyers who purchase a 5ct pear lab grown ring should consider it as a jewelry purchase rather than an investment vehicle.

